      "announcement_url": null,
      "experiment_goals": "We aim to validate the JPEG XL decoder's real-world performance and adoption patterns through the following metrics:\n\n- Decode Performance: Using Renderer4.ImageDecodeTaskDurationUs.Jxl.{Gpu,Software} to measure decode latency across\n   different hardware configurations.\n- Compression Efficiency: Using Blink.DecodedImage.JxlDensity.Count.{ImageArea} to understand what compression ratios\n  (bits-per-pixel) developers are using in practice across different image sizes, validating whether the format delivers\n  expected bandwidth savings.\n- Adoption Patterns: Tracking Blink.DecodedImageType to measure JXL adoption relative to other formats and understand which\n  use cases (image sizes, types) developers prioritize.\n- Stability & Compatibility: Monitoring crash reports and decoder errors to ensure robust handling of diverse JXL content\n  in production environments.\n\nThis experiment is well-suited for Origin Trial limits since we're gathering aggregate telemetry rather than requiring\ndeployment at scale—smaller sites and early adopters can provide meaningful signal on decode performance and compression\npatterns.",
      "experiment_risks": "Minimal risk. JPEG XL is a stateless image decoding format with no persistent data or storage implications.\n\nIf the experiment ends:\n- No data loss: JXL is purely a display format—no user data, storage, or state is tied to it.\n- Graceful degradation: Sites using JXL can (and should) provide fallback formats via the <picture> element or content\n  negotiation, which is standard practice for modern image formats.\n- No broken functionality: Images simply won't render if JXL support is removed; sites fall back to JPEG/WebP/PNG\n  alternatives.\n\nThis is identical to how WebP and AVIF were introduced—image formats carry inherently low risk since they don't create\ndependencies on persistent browser state.",
